  "prompt": "How many times in a day are the hands of a clock in straight line but opposite in direction?",
  "response": "Alright, let's tackle this problem step by step. The question is: **\"How many times in a day are the hands of a clock in a straight line but opposite in direction?\"**\n\nFirst, let's understand what it means for the clock hands to be in a straight line but opposite in direction. This essentially means that the hour and minute hands are 180 degrees apart, pointing directly away from each other. Think of times like 6:00, where the hour hand points at 6 and the minute hand points at 12.\n\n### Understanding the Basics\n\n1. **Clock Mechanics:**\n   - A clock has 12 hours on its face.\n   - The minute hand completes a full circle (360 degrees) every 60 minutes.\n   - The hour hand completes a full circle every 12 hours.\n\n2. **Total Degrees in a Circle:**\n   - Any circle, including a clock, has 360 degrees.\n\n3. **Speed of the Hands:**\n   - **Minute Hand:** 360 degrees every 60 minutes \u2192 6 degrees per minute.\n   - **Hour Hand:** 360 degrees every 12 hours \u2192 0.5 degrees per minute.\n\n### Calculating When the Hands are 180 Degrees Apart\n\nWe need to find the instances when the angle between the hour and minute hands is exactly 180 degrees.\n\nThe formula to find the angle \u03b8 between the hour and minute hands at a given time **H** hours and **M** minutes is:\n\n\u03b8 = |30H - 5.5M|\n\nFor the hands to be opposite, \u03b8 should be 180 degrees. So, we set up the equation:\n\n|30H - 5.5M| = 180\n\nThis equation can be split into two cases:\n\n1. **Case 1:** 30H - 5.5M = 180\n2. **Case 2:** 30H - 5.5M = -180\n\nLet's solve each case separately to find the times when the hands are opposite each other.\n\n#### Case 1: 30H - 5.5M = 180\n\nSolving for M:\n\n30H - 5.5M = 180  \n-5.5M = 180 - 30H  \nM = (180 - 30H) / (-5.5)  \nM = -(180 - 30H) / 5.5  \nM = (30H - 180) / 5.5\n\n#### Case 2: 30H - 5.5M = -180\n\nSolving for M:\n\n30H - 5.5M = -180  \n-5.5M = -180 - 30H  \nM = (-180 - 30H) / (-5.5)  \nM = (180 + 30H) / 5.5\n\nNow, let's simplify these expressions to make them easier to work with.\n\n### Simplifying the Equations\n\nLet's manipulate both equations to solve for M in terms of H.\n\n#### Simplifying Case 1:\n\nM = (30H - 180) / 5.5\n\nWe can factor out 30 from the numerator:\n\nM = 30(H - 6) / 5.5\n\nTo eliminate decimals, multiply numerator and denominator by 2:\n\nM = [30(H - 6) * 2] / [5.5 * 2]  \nM = 60(H - 6) / 11  \nM = (60/11)(H - 6)\n\n(Note: 60/11 \u2248 5.4545)\n\nSimilarly, let's simplify Case 2:\n\n#### Simplifying Case 2:\n\nM = (180 + 30H) / 5.5\n\nFactor out 30 from the numerator:\n\nM = 30(H + 6) / 5.5\n\nMultiply numerator and by 2:\n\nM = [30(H + 6) * 2] / [5.5 * 2]  \nM = 60(H + 6) / 11  \nM = (60/11)(H + 6)\n\n(Note: 60/11 \u2248 5.4545)\n\n### Finding Times When Hands are Opposite\n\nNow, let's find the specific times using these formulas. Remember, H represents the hour (ranging from 0 to 12), and M represents the minutes past the hour.\n\n#### Case 1: M = (60/11)(H - 6)\n\nLet's calculate M for each hour from 1 to 12:\n\n1. **H = 1:** M = (60/11)(1 - 6) = (60/11)(-5) \u2248 -27.27 minutes  \n   (Negative time doesn't make sense in this context, so H = 1 is not valid.)\n\n2. **H = 2:** M = (60/11)(2 - 6) = (60/11)(-4) \u2248 -21.82 minutes  \n   (Invalid.)\n\n3. **H = 3:** M = (60/11)(3 - 6) = (60/11)(-3) \u2248 -16.36 minutes  \n   (Invalid.)\n\n4. **H = 4:** M = (60/11)(4 - 6) = (60/11)(-2) \u2248 -10.91 minutes  \n   (Invalid.)\n\n5. **H = 5:** M = (60/11)(5 - 6) = (60/11)(-1) \u2248 -5.45 minutes  \n   (Invalid.)\n\n6. **H = 6:** M = (60/11)(6 - 6) = (60/11)(0) = 0 minutes  \n   Valid time: 6:00\n\n7. **H = 7:** M = (60/11)(7 - 6) = (60/11)(1) \u2248 5.45 minutes  \n   Valid time: 7:05 and 27 seconds (approximately 7:05:27)\n\n8. **H = 8:** M = (60/11)(8 - 6) = (60/11)(2) \u2248 10.91 minutes  \n   Valid time: 8:10 and 55 seconds (approximately 8:10:55)\n\n9. **H = 9:** M = (60/11)(9 - 6) = (60/11)(3) \u2248 16.36 minutes  \n   Valid time: 9:16 and 21 seconds (approximately 9:16:21)\n\n10. **H = 10:** M = (60/11)(10 - 6) = (60/11)(4) \u2248 21.82 minutes  \n    Valid time: 10:21 and 49 seconds (approximately 10:21:49)\n\n11. **H = 11:** M = (60/11)(11 - 6) = (60/11)(5) \u2248 27.27 minutes  \n    Valid time: 11:27 and 16 seconds (approximately 11:27:16)\n\n12. **H = 12:** M = (60/11)(12 - 6) = (60/11)(6) \u2248 32.73 minutes  \n    Wait, H = 12 is essentially the same as H = 0 in a 12-hour clock, and we've already considered 6:00. So, H = 12 would repeat the cycle.\n\n#### Case 2: M = (60/11)(H + 6)\n\nSimilarly, let's calculate M for each hour from 1 to 12:\n\n1. **H = 1:** M = (60/11)(1 + 6) = (60/11)(7) \u2248 38.18 minutes  \n   Valid time: 1:38 and 11 seconds (approximately 1:38:11)\n\n2. **H = 2:** M = (60/11)(2 + 6) = (60/11)(8) \u2248 43.64 minutes  \n   Valid time: 2:43 and 38 seconds (approximately 2:43:38)\n\n3. **H = 3:** M = (60/11)(3 + 6) = (60/11)(9) \u2248 49.09 minutes  \n   Valid time: 3:49 and 5 seconds (approximately 3:49:05)\n\n4. **H = 4:** M = (60/11)(4 + 6) = (60/11)(10) \u2248 54.55 minutes  \n   Valid time: 4:54 and 33 seconds (approximately 4:54:33)\n\n5. **H = 5:** M = (60/11)(5 + 6) = (60/11)(11) = 60 minutes  \n   Valid time: 6:00  \n   (But wait, this brings us back to H = 6, which we've already considered.)\n\n6. **H = 6:** M = (60/11)(6 + 6) = (60/11)(12) \u2248 65.45 minutes  \n   Wait, 65.45 minutes is equivalent to 1 hour and 5.45 minutes, which would correspond to 7:05 and 27 seconds, which we've already considered in Case 1.\n\n7. **H = 7:** M = (60/11)(7 + 6) = (60/11)(13) \u2248 70.91 minutes  \n   Which is approximately 1 hour and 10.91 minutes, placing us at 8:10 and 55 seconds, already considered in Case 1.\n\n8. **H = 8:** M = (60/11)(8 + 6) = (60/11)(14) \u2248 76.36 minutes  \n   Which is approximately 1 hour and 16.36 minutes, placing us at 9:16 and 21 seconds, already considered in Case 1.\n\n9. **H = 9:** M = (60/11)(9 + 6) = (60/11)(15) \u2248 81.82 minutes  \n   Which is approximately 1 hour and 21.82 minutes, placing us at 10:21 and 49 seconds, already considered in Case 1.\n\n10. **H = 10:** M = (60/11)(10 + 6) = (60/11)(16) \u2248 87.27 minutes  \n    Which is approximately 1 hour and 27.27 minutes, placing us at 11:27 and 16 seconds, already considered in Case 1.\n\n11. **H = 11:** M = (60/11)(11 + 6) = (60/11)(17) \u2248 92.73 minutes  \n    Which is approximately 1 hour and 32.73 minutes, bringing us to the next hour, which would essentially repeat the cycle.\n\n12. **H = 12:** M = (60/11)(12 + 6) = (60/11)(18) \u2248 98.18 minutes  \n    Which is approximately 1 hour and 38.18 minutes, but H = 12 is essentially H = 0, and we've already covered this in Case 1.\n\n### Compiling the Valid Times\n\nFrom both cases, we have the following valid times when the hands are opposite each other:\n\n- **6:00**\n- **Approximately 7:05:27**\n- **Approximately 8:10:55**\n- **Approximately 9:16:21**\n- **Approximately 10:21:49**\n- **Approximately 11:27:16**\n  \nThese are the instances between 12:00 PM and 11:59 PM (since we're considering a 12-hour clock).\n\nBut remember, a day has 24 hours, so we need to consider another 12-hour cycle from 12:00 AM to 11:59 AM.\n\nIn the next 12-hour cycle (the first half of the day), the times will be the same as above:\n\n- **12:00 AM (same as 12:00 PM hour-wise)**\n- **Approximately 1:05:27 AM**\n- **Approximately 2:10:55 AM**\n- **Approximately 3:16:21 AM**\n- **Approximately 4:21:49 AM**\n- **Approximately 5:27:16 AM**\n\n### Total Number of Opposite Times in a Day\n\nSo, in a 12-hour period, there are 6 times when the hands are opposite each other.\n\nSince a day has two 12-hour periods (AM and PM), we multiply 6 by 2:\n\n6 times (AM) + 6 times (PM) = **12 times**\n\n### Verification\n\nTo ensure our answer is correct, let's verify by considering the speed of the clock hands.\n\nEvery 12 hours, the clock completes a full cycle. During this time, the minute and hour hands align or are opposite every 60/(1 - 1/12) = 60/(11/12) = 720/11 \u2248 65.45 minutes.\n\nSince there are 720 minutes in 12 hours, and the hands are opposite each other every 720/11 minutes, we get:\n\nTotal instances = 720 / (720/11) = 11\n\nWait, that seems to contradict our earlier calculation of 6 times in 12 hours.\n\nLet's re-examine this.\n\nIf the hands are opposite every 720/11 minutes (\u2248 65.45 minutes), and there are 720 minutes in 12 hours, then:\n\nNumber of instances = Total time / Time between instances = 720 / (720/11) = 11\n\nBut initially, we found 6 times in 12 hours using the angle method.\n\nThis discrepancy suggests there's a miscalculation.\n\nLet's revisit the angle method.\n\n### Revisiting the Angle Method\n\nUpon closer inspection, when we solve |30H - 5.5M| = 180, we get two cases:\n\n1. 30H - 198 = 5.5M \u21d2 M = (30H - 180)/5.5\n2. 30H = 5.5M - 180 \u21d2 M = (30H + 180)/5.5\n\nSolving these:\n\n**Case 1:** M = (30H - 180)/5.5 = (60/11)(H - 6)\n\n**Case 2:** M = (30H + 180)/5.5 = (60/11)(H + 6)\n\nNow, analyzing these:\n\n**Case 1:** We get valid times starting from H = 6 onwards (6:00, \u22487:05:27, \u22488:10:55, \u22489:16:21, \u224810:21:49, \u224811:27:16)\n\n**Case 2:** We get valid times starting from H = 1 onwards (\u22481:38:11, \u22482:43:38, \u22483:49:05, \u22484:54:33, and then it wraps around)\n\nLet's list all times carefully:\n\n**Case 1:**\n\n- 6:00\n- 7:05:27\n- 8:10:55\n- 9:16:21\n- 10:21:49\n- 11:27:16\n\n**Case 2:**\n\n- 1:38:11\n- 2:43:38\n- 3:49:05\n- 4:54:33\n- 6:00 (already counted in Case 1)\n- 7:05:27 (already counted)\n- And so on...\n\nSo, total unique times in 12 hours:\n\nFrom Case 1: 6 times  \nFrom Case 2: 4 times (excluding overlaps with Case 1)\n\nTotal: 6 + 4 = **10 times** in 12 hours\n\nTherefore, in 24 hours: 10 times (AM) + 10 times (PM) = **20 times**\n\nWait, but earlier using the speed method, we got 11 times in 12 hours. Here, we got 10. There's still inconsistency.\n\nThere must be a mistake in counting.\n\nLet's recount carefully.\n\n### Accurate Counting of Opposite Times\n\nLet's list all possible times when the hands are opposite in both cases without overlapping.\n\n**Case 1:**\n\n1. 6:00\n2. 7:05:27\n3. 8:10:55\n4. 9:16:21\n5. 10:21:49\n6. 11:27:16\n\n**Case 2:**\n\n1. 1:38:11\n2. 2:43:38\n3. 3:49:05\n4. 4:54:33\n5. 6:00 (already in Case 1)\n6. 7:05:27 (already in Case 1)\n7. 8:10:55 (already in Case 1)\n8. 9:16:21 (already in Case 1)\n9. 10:21:49 (already in Case 1)\n10. 11:27:16 (already in Case 1)\n\nSo, total unique times:\n\nFrom Case 1: 6 times  \nFrom Case 2: 4 times (excluding the times already in Case 1)\n\nTotal: 6 + 4 = **10 times** in 12 hours\n\nTherefore, in 24 hours: 10 times (AM) + 10 times (PM) = **20 times**\n\nBut the speed method suggested 11 times in 12 hours, resulting in 22 times in 24 hours.\n\nThis discrepancy indicates an error in the speed method's application.\n\n### Correcting the Speed Method Logic\n\nThe speed method calculates the frequency of the hands being opposite based on their relative speeds.\n\nThe minute hand moves at 360 degrees per hour, and the hour hand moves at 30 degrees per hour.\n\nRelative speed: 360 - 30 = 330 degrees per hour.\n\nThey are opposite when the minute hand gains 180 degrees on the hour hand.\n\nTime taken to gain 180 degrees:\n\nTime = Angle / Relative speed = 180 / 330 = 6/11 hours\n\nConvert to minutes: (6/11) * 60 \u2248 32.73 minutes\n\nBut this is incorrect because they are opposite every 65.45 minutes, not 32.73 minutes.\n\nSo, correct time between opposite alignments:\n\nSince the hands gain 360 degrees relative to each other in 12/11 hours (since 360 / 330 = 12/11 hours), they are opposite every 6/11 of this time.\n\nWait, let's re-express this clearly.\n\nThe hands return to the same alignment every 12/11 hours.\n\nSo, they are opposite halfway between alignments: (12/11)/2 = 6/11 hours = \u224832.73 minutes\n\nTherefore, in 12 hours, the number of opposite alignments = 12 / (6/11) = 22\n\nBut this contradicts our angle method result of 11 times in 12 hours.\n\nWait, let's re-examine.\n\nIf they are opposite every 32.73 minutes, then in 720 minutes:\n\nNumber of opposite times = 720 / 32.73 \u2248 22\n\nBut the angle method gave us 10 times in 12 hours.\n\nThis inconsistency suggests a flaw in one of the methods.\n\nPerhaps the angle method missed some cases.\n\n### Re-examning the Angle Method\n\nLet's solve the equation |30H - 5.5M| = 180 more carefully.\n\nWe have two equations:\n\n1. 30H - 5.5M = 180 \u21d2 M = (30H - 180)/5.5 = (60/11)(H - 6)\n2. 30H - 5.5M = -180 \u21d2 M = (30H + 180)/5.5 = (60/11)(H + 6)\n\nLet's solve for each hour H from 1 to 12.\n\n**Case 1: M = (60/11)(H - 6)**\n\n1. H = 1: M = (60/11)(-5) \u2248 -27.27 (Invalid)\n2. H = 2: M = (60/11)(-4) \u2248 -21.82 (Invalid)\n3. H = 3: M = (60/11)(-3) \u2248 -16.36 (Invalid)\n4. H = 4: M = (60/11)(-2) \u2248 -10.91 (Invalid)\n5. H = 5: M = (60/11)(-1) \u2248 -5.45 (Invalid)\n6. H = 6: M = (60/11)(0) = 0 \u21d2 6:00\n7. H = 7: M = (60/11)(1) \u2248 5.45 \u21d2 7:05:27\n8. H = 8: M = (60/11)(2) \u2248 10.91 \u21d2 8:10:55\n9. H = 9: M = (60/11)(3) \u2248 16.36 \u21d2 9:16:21\n10. H = 10: M = (60/11)(4) \u2248 21.82 \u21d2 10:21:49\n11. H = 11: M = (60/11)(5) \u2248 27.27 \u21d2 11:27:16\n12. H = 12: M = (60/11)(6) \u2248 32.73 \u21d2 12:32:44\n\n**Case 2: M = (60/11)(H + 6)**\n\n1. H = 1: M = (60/11)(7) \u2248 38.18 \u21d2 1:38:11\n2. H = 2: M = (60/11)(8) \u2248 43.64 \u21d2 2:43:38\n3. H = 3: M = (60/11)(9) \u2248 49.09 \u21d2 3:49:05\n4. H = 4: M = (60/11)(10) \u2248 54.55 \u21d2 4:54:33\n5. H = 5: M = (60/11)(11) = 60 \u21d2 6:00 (already counted)\n6. H = 6: M = (60/11)(12) \u2248 65.45 \u21d2 1 hour and 5.45 minutes \u21d2 7:05:27 (already counted)\n7. H = 7: M = (60/11)(13) \u2248 70.91 \u21d2 1 hour and 10.91 minutes \u21d2 8:10:55 (already counted)\n8. H = 8: M = (60/11)(14) \u2248 76.36 \u21d2 1 hour and 16.36 minutes \u21d2 9:16:21 (already counted)\n9. H = 9: M = (60/11)(15) \u2248 81.82 \u21d2 1 hour and 21.82 minutes \u21d2 10:21:49 (already counted)\n10. H = 10: M = (60/11)(16) \u2248 87.27 \u21d2 1 hour and 27.27 minutes \u21d2 11:27:16 (already counted)\n11. H = 11: M = (60/11)(17) \u2248 92.73 \u21d2 1 hour and 32.73 minutes \u21d2 Next hour 0:32:44 (12:32:44 already counted)\n12. H = 12: M = (60/11)(18) \u2248 98.18 \u21d2 1 hour and 38.18 minutes \u21d2 Next hour 1:38:11 (already counted)\n\nNow, compiling all unique valid times from both cases:\n\nFrom **Case 1:**\n\n1. 6:00\n2. 7:05:27\n3. 8:10:55\n4. 9:16:21\n5. 10:21:49\n6. 11:27:16\n7. 12:32:44 (This is new!)\n\nFrom **Case 2:**\n\n1. 1:38:11\n2. 2:43:38\n3. 3:49:05\n4. 4:54:33\n\nTotal unique times in 12 hours: 11\n\nTherefore, in 24 hours: 11 times (AM) + 11 times (PM) = **22 times**\n\nThis aligns with the speed method's result.\n\n### Conclusion\n\nAfter carefully analyzing both the angle method and the speed method, we conclude that in a 12-hour period, the hour and minute hands of a clock are in a straight line but opposite in direction **11 times**. Therefore, in a full 24-hour day, this occurs **22 times**.\n\n**Final Answer:** The hands of a clock are in a straight line but opposite in direction **22 times** in a day.",
